{"title_page": "Battlefield V", "text_new": "{{Short description|2018 video game}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox video game\n| title = Battlefield V\n| image = Battlefield_V_standard_edition_box_art.jpg\n| developer = [[EA DICE]]{{efn|Additional work by [[Criterion Games]]}}\n| publisher = [[Electronic Arts]]\n| series = ''[[Battlefield (video game series)|Battlefield]]''\n| producer = {{Unbulleted list|Aleksander Gr\u00f8ndal|Andreas Morell|David Sirland|Lars Gustavsson|Ryan McArthur}}\n| designer = {{Unbulleted list|Daniel Berlin|Nathalie Ek|Ross Darvill}}\n| programmer = \n| artist = {{Unbulleted list|Carlos Villarreal Kwasek|Conny Bergqvist|Fabien Christin|Joakim Stigsson}}\n| writer = [[Steven Hall (author)|Steven Hall]]\n| composer = {{Unbulleted list|Patrik Andr\u00e9n<br />[[Johan S\u00f6derqvist]]}}\n| engine = [[Frostbite (game engine)|Frostbite 3]]\n| platforms = {{Unbulleted list|[[Microsoft Windows]]|[[PlayStation 4]]|[[Xbox One]]}}\n| released = November 20, 2018<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ea.com/games/battlefield/news/an-update-on-battlefield-5#__prclt=xWIFxy0y|title=An Update on Battlefield V|publisher=[[Electronic Arts]]|date=August 30, 2018|access-date=October 22, 2018}}</ref>\n| genre = [[First-person shooter]], [[Battle royale game|battle royale]]\n| modes = [[Single-player video game|Single-player]], [[Multiplayer video game|multiplayer]]\n}}\n\n'''''Battlefield V''''' is a [[first-person shooter]] [[video game]] developed by [[EA DICE]] and published by [[Electronic Arts]]. ''Battlefield V'' is the sixteenth installment in the ''[[Battlefield (video game series)|Battlefield]]'' series. It was released worldwide for [[Microsoft Windows]], [[PlayStation 4]], and [[Xbox One]] on November 20, 2018. Those who pre-ordered the Deluxe Edition of the game were granted early access to the game on November 15, 2018,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2018/10/18/complete-guide-to-battlefield-5-preorder-bonuses|title=Complete Guide to Battlefield 5 Preorder Bonuses|last=Macy|first=Seth G.|website=IGN|date=October 18, 2018|access-date=November 2, 2018}}</ref> and [[Origin Access]] Premium subscribers on PC received access to the game on November 9, 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.polygon.com/2018/11/9/18079060/battlefield-5-ea-subscribers-early-release-date|title=Players who buy Battlefield 5 have to wait the longest to play it|work=Polygon|access-date=November 9, 2018}}</ref> The game is based on [[World War II]] and is a thematic continuation of its [[World War I]] based precursor ''[[Battlefield 1]]''.\n\nPre-release reception of the game was mixed, with the announcement trailer causing backlash from some fans of the series for the degree of historical inaccuracy regarding the game's depictions of female soldiers. Upon release, ''Battlefield V'' received generally favourable reviews from critics, being praised for its gameplay but criticized for its shortage of content at launch and lack of innovation. The game sold 7.3 million copies by the end of 2018 but was a commercial disappointment for Electronic Arts. \n\nOn April 23 2020 it was announced that live service for the game would continue until summer of 2020, when the game would receive its last major update.<ref>{{cite web |title=An update on the future of Battlefield V |url=https://twitter.com/Battlefield/status/1253307936962678784 |website=Twitter |publisher=Battlefield |accessdate=23 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Correct, and we'll have more details about what's included in the summer update closer to that time. |url=https://twitter.com/Battlefield/status/1253314285201051649 |website=Twitter |publisher=Battlefield |accessdate=23 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Gameplay ==\n''Battlefield V'' is focused extensively on party-based features and mechanics, scarcity of resources, and removing \"abstractions\" from game mechanics to increase realism.<ref name=\"vergereturn\" /> There is an expanded focus on player customization through the new [[Company (military unit)|Company]] system, where players can create multiple characters with cosmetic and weapon options. Cosmetic items, and currency used to purchase others, are earned by completing in-game objectives.<ref name=\"vergereturn\" /><ref name=\"polygoncustom\">{{cite news|url=https://www.polygon.com/2018/5/23/17385040/battlefield-5-character-customization-items|last=Gilliam|first=Ryan|date=May 23, 2018|title=Players can customize every aspect of their characters in Battlefield 5|work=Polygon|access-date=May 24, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180530130700/https://www.polygon.com/2018/5/23/17385040/battlefield-5-character-customization-items|archive-date=May 30, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"polygon-nopass\" />\n\nThe game features several new multiplayer modes, including the \"continuous\" campaign mode \"[[Battle royale game|Firestorm]]\", and \"Grand Operations\". The Grand Operations mode is an expansion of the \"Operations\" mode introduced in ''Battlefield 1'', which focuses on matches taking place across multiple stages to simulate a campaign from the war. In Grand Operations, each round will have specific objectives, and performance in each stage will influence the next. If the final day ends with a close margin of victory, the match will culminate with a \"Final Stand,\" with players fighting to the last man standing on a continually shrinking map. Similarly to ''Battlefield 1'', the game features a collection of single-player \"war stories\" based on aspects of World War II.<ref name=\"vergereturn\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theverge.com/2018/5/23/17384042/battlefield-5-release-date-trailer-video|last=Savov|first=Vlad|title=Battlefield V returns to World War II this October|work=The Verge|date=May 23, 2018|access-date=May 23, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180530130250/https://www.theverge.com/2018/5/23/17384042/battlefield-5-release-date-trailer-video|archive-date=May 30, 2018}}</ref> The game also features a [[cooperative gameplay|cooperative]] mode not seen since ''[[Battlefield 3]]'' called \"Combined Arms,\" where up to four players can undertake missions together and features dynamic missions and objectives so missions cannot be played the same way each time.\n\nThe [[Battle royale game|battle royale]] mode is built around the franchise's \"core pillars of destruction, team play, and vehicles.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2018-06-09-battlefield-v-is-getting-a-battle-royale-mode-called-royale|title=Battlefield V is getting a battle royale mode called Royale|work=Eurogamer.net|access-date=June 14, 2018|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.trustedreviews.com/news/battlefield-5-release-date-3231890|last=|first=|title=Battlefield 5: EA announces Battle Royale mode at E3 2018|work=TrustedReviews|date=June 9, 2018|access-date=June 9, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/e3-2018-battlefield-5-battle-royale-mode-announced/1100-6459536/|last=|first=|title=E3 2018: Battlefield 5 Battle Royale Mode Announced By EA|work=GameSpot|date=June 9, 2018|access-date=June 9, 2018}}</ref> The name \"Firestorm\" refers to a literal storm of fire that constricts players similar to the popular Battle Royale game mechanic of restricting the play area. Furthermore, this particular game mode was not developed by EA DICE themselves, but has been outsourced to [[Criterion Games]] and features the biggest map created by the franchise to date. It is playable by 64 players, which can be divided into up to 16 squads with a focus on team work.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2018-09-07-burnout-creator-criterion-making-battlefield-5s-battle-royale-mode|title=Criterion making Battlefield 5's battle royale mode|first=Tom|last=Phillips|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=September 7, 2018|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Synopsis ==\nAs in ''Battlefield 1'', the single-player campaign is divided into an introduction followed by episodic ''War Stories,'' three of which were available at launch: ''\"Nordlys\"'' takes place from the point-of-view of a [[Norwegian resistance movement|Norwegian resistance]] fighter taking part in the [[Norwegian heavy water sabotage|sabotage of the German nuclear program]], ''\"Tirailleur\"'' tells the story of a [[Senegalese Tirailleurs|Senegalese Tirailleur]] during [[Operation Dragoon]], and ''\"Under No Flag\"'' puts the player in the shoes of Billy Bridger, a convicted bank robber and explosives expert conscripted into the [[Special Boat Service]] to take part in [[Operation Albumen]]. The fourth campaign, ''\"The Last Tiger,\"'' was released on December 5, 2018, which depicts the struggles of a German [[Tiger I]] tank crew during the [[Ruhr Pocket]] in the closing days of the war.\n\n=== My Country Calling ===\nThe introductory episode of Battlefield V, titled \u201cMy Country Calling\u201d or \u201cPrologue\u201d, is a tutorial required upon first launching up the game. In it, the player learns the basic mechanics on how infantry, tanks, and planes, as well as setting the tone for future war stories. The prologue begins after Battlefield 1's \u201cStorm of Steel\u201d left off, before cutting to a black screen with white text, commentating on how society was quick to forget the horrors of the First World War. The prologue then jumps forward to London 1939, with Neville Chamberlain's declaration of war on Germany being played on the radio. The narration then begins before the player steps into the shoes of a British paratrooper, during a night raid at Narvik Docks, 1940. The player then must defeat several German soldiers before a Tiger I tank appears, and the screen fades to white. The player is then placed into control of tank commander Peter Muller, the main character of the \u201cLast Tiger\u201d war story. In this instance, however, the player is tasked with breaking British lines at Tobruk, before an artillery strike causes another character change. After the transition, the player is then put in control of a free French sniper, presumed to be one of the same soldiers as the \u201cTirailleur\u201d war story, around the Kasserine Pass. After sniping several enemies during an ambush sequence, the player character is then killed when a strafing run hits them. The camera then pans to a Bf 109 pilot titled Yellow-Seven. This time, the player must shoot down a variety of Blenheim and Spitfire aircraft, before being shot down themselves. Finally, the player takes the role of a British machine gunner during the Final Defense at Nijmegen Bridge, 1944. A V1 flying bomb soon detonates on their position, however, and the player goes into a last stand before getting killed in the onslaught of gunfire. Upon completion of all introductory segments, the player is then shown cinematic clips of the war stories, before being treated to the game's title card.\n\n=== Under No Flag ===\nIn the spring of 1942, convicted bank robber William Sidney \"Billy\" Bridger, the son of another infamous bank robber, Arthur Bridger, volunteers to join the British military in order to avoid jail time, and is assigned as a demolitions expert to a Special Boat Service team led by George Mason ([[Craig Fairbrass]]). Billy and Mason infiltrate occupied North Africa in order to sabotage German airfields. However, things don't go as planned at the first airfield; one of Billy's bombs (\"safecracker specials\") fails to detonate, much to Mason's anger, forcing Billy to commandeer an anti-aircraft gun to destroy the final plane. Mason is wounded, and after an argument with Mason about whose fault it was that Mason could have been killed, Billy and Mason steal a German's car and drive to the second airfield. However, due to Mason's wounds, Billy is forced to infiltrate the airfield alone. Billy is able to destroy the objectives, but detours to a nearby bunker to collect medical supplies for Mason, and uses the radio there to call HMS ''Sussex'' for evacuation. After destroying the base's radar stations, Billy returns to report to Mason. However, Mason is furious when he finds out Billy radioed for help, since it would alert the Germans to their exact location. A massive German force begins to pursue them and they are forced to hide in some ruins. Billy begins to express doubts at his own competence and their chances of survival, as well as grieving over his failure to please his father. Mason confides in Billy that he picked him to volunteer for the unit because his many attempts to rob banks, especially three of one bank, showed him as a \"tryer,\" a person who doesn't easily give up. Inspired, Billy fights alongside Mason in a last stand. They manage to hold off the German forces long enough for British reinforcements to arrive, and the Germans are subsequently routed. In the aftermath, Billy and Mason have a newfound respect for each other as they head off for their next mission.\n\n=== Nordlys ===\nIn the spring of 1943, in Rjukjan, Norway, a British commando unit is killed attempting to infiltrate a German occupied facility and Astrid, the Norwegian resistance fighter assisting them, is captured. Meanwhile, Astrid's daughter Solveig fights her way into the facility to rescue her. However, Astrid refuses to leave, insisting that the facility must be destroyed first since it is producing heavy water for Germany's nuclear weapon research. The pair manage to sabotage the facility, but much of the heavy water is evacuated by truck. They attempt to pursue, but are cornered on a bridge by German forces commanded by [[Leutnant]] Weber. Entrusting Solveig with the mission to destroy the heavy water, Astrid pushes her off the bridge to prevent her from being captured. Narrowly surviving the fall, Solveig carries on the mission, pursuing the trucks and destroying all of them. Unfortunately, the Germans have already loaded Astrid and some of the heavy water on board a U-boat, and Solveig is unable to board it. Astrid steals a grenade and uses it to destroy the U-boat and the heavy water, killing herself and Weber in the process. It is left unclear whether Solveig survived the explosion or not.\n\n=== Tirailleur ===\nIn the autumn of 1944 after the Allied [[landings at Normandy]], Senegalese soldiers are sent to help liberate France from German occupation. One of these soldiers is the young recruit Deme Cisse, who meets fellow soldier and older brother Idrissa upon arriving in France. However, Deme quickly experiences discrimination from the French army, with the Senegalese being blocked from fighting on the frontlines and instead assigned to perform menial tasks such as filling sandbags. Finally, the Senegalese are allowed to participate in an assault on a heavily fortified German position by moving to destroy a set of anti-aircraft guns defending the area. The Senegalese are ambushed on the way to their objective, but they are able to capture and hold a German strongpoint. Idrissa is reluctant to proceed further since their commanders are dead and they have no support, but Deme is determined to keep pushing to the anti-aircraft guns in order to win recognition from the French army, and he convinces the rest of the unit to follow him. They are successful in destroying the anti-aircraft guns, but suffer heavy casualties in the process. In addition, a wounded German soldier boasts they will be surrounded, destroyed in the inevitable counterattack, and that nobody will know they were even there. A hopeless Idrissa, fearing that he won't come home to his family alive, considers withdrawing, but Deme insists that they do what the Germans won't expect them to: directly attack the German headquarters. They manage to break into the headquarters, but are ambushed by a Tiger tank. Idrissa is mortally wounded after destroying the Tiger, much to Deme's shock. Despite Deme's unit having taken the headquarters, their involvement in the operation is covered up and forgotten. In the present, an elderly Deme recounts his story and declares that no matter what happens, nothing can erase what he and his comrades had done, and that he is proud of it.\n\n=== The Last Tiger ===\nIn the spring of 1945, veteran [[Tiger I]] commander Peter M\u00fcller and his tank crew participates in the defense of the [[Rhine-Ruhr]] against invading American forces, with orders from High Command that all German soldiers must fight to the death. After surviving a series of heavy engagements, the Tiger is forced to take cover from Allied bombers. At the behest of Schr\u00f6der, the crew's young and fanatically patriotic gunner, M\u00fcller has young loader Hartmann scout the ruins ahead for a passage through. A large American tank column suddenly appears, forcing the crew to leave Hartmann behind. The Tiger receives orders to regroup at the cathedral with other remaining German forces for a final defense; en route, they discover Hartmann had been executed by [[hanging]] along with several other accused deserters. They reach the cathedral, only to find it abandoned and are quickly surrounded by the American army, who demand their surrender. With new orders to defend their position, the crew fights off the enemy before making their way to the bridge, which leads back to German lines. The bridge is suddenly destroyed by a series of explosions, and the Tiger is disabled. Kertz, the crew's veteran driver, expresses his disillusionment in the German cause and decides to desert despite M\u00fcller's pleading; Kertz is then shot and fatally wounded by Schr\u00f6der. As M\u00fcller cradles his friend's corpse, American soldiers arrive and again demand their surrender, but the fanatical Schr\u00f6der continues to fight. M\u00fcller discards his [[Knight's Cross of the Iron Cross|Knight's Cross]] and raises his arms in surrender, after which an enraged Schr\u00f6der aims his [[MP40]] at him. The screen cuts to black and a burst of gunfire is heard, leaving M\u00fcller's fate ambiguous.\n\n== Development ==\nDICE unveiled the first details surrounding ''Battlefield V'' on May 23, 2018, with more information to be unveiled during the EA Play press conference near [[E3 2018]] in June. DICE has stated that, unlike ''Battlefield 1'', it does not plan to use paid [[downloadable content]], or \"[[loot box]]es\" for non-cosmetic items within ''Battlefield V''; new content will be added to the game for all players over time (which, itself, will progress through the different stages of World War II), at no additional charge.<ref name=\"polygon-nopass\">{{cite news|url=https://www.polygon.com/2018/5/23/17384662/battlefield-5-premium-pass|title=Battlefield 5 ditches the premium pass|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180524115940/https://www.polygon.com/2018/5/23/17384662/battlefield-5-premium-pass|archive-date=May 24, 2018|work=Polygon|access-date=May 23, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://variety.com/2018/gaming/news/battlefield-v-details-1202819935/|title=\u2018Battlefield V\u2019 Hits Oct. 19, Explores WWII Free of Premium Pass, Loot Boxes|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180524120154/http://variety.com/2018/gaming/news/battlefield-v-details-1202819935/|archive-date=May 24, 2018|last=Crecente|first=Brian|date=May 23, 2018|work=Variety|access-date=May 23, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> The decision to exclude these features was made following the outrage over the loot box system in ''[[Star Wars Battlefront II (2017 video game)|Star Wars Battlefront II]]'', another EA DICE title.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://kotaku.com/heres-our-first-look-at-battlefield-v-which-goes-back-1826271285|title=Here's Our First Look At Battlefield V, Which Goes Back To WWII|work=Kotaku|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180524115705/https://kotaku.com/heres-our-first-look-at-battlefield-v-which-goes-back-1826271285|archive-date=May 24, 2018|access-date=May 24, 2018|date=May 23, 2018|last=Scheirer|first=Jason}}</ref> The game was originally set to release on October 19, but was delayed to November 20 to enable the developers to \"make some final adjustments to core gameplay.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pcgamer.com/battlefield-5-release-date-delayed-to-november/|title=Battlefield 5 release date delayed to November|publisher=}}</ref> It is one of the first major games to make use of real-time [[ray tracing (graphics)|ray tracing]] and [[DLSS]], with help from [[Nvidia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tomshardware.com/reviews/battlefield-5-ray-tracing-benchmarks,5911.html|title=Here's How Battlefield V Performs with Ray Tracing|last=Angelini|first=Chris|last2=Freedman|first2=Andrew E.|work=Tom's Hardware|date=November 16, 2018|access-date=October 15, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.techspot.com/article/1794-nvidia-rtx-dlss-battlefield/| title=Battlefield V DLSS Tested: Overpromised, Underdelivered| publisher=techspot.com| date=2019-02-19| accessdate=2020-04-06| quote=''Of course, this is to be expected. DLSS was never going to provide the same image quality as native 4K, while providing a 37% performance uplift. That would be black magic. But the quality difference comparing the two is almost laughable, in how far away DLSS is from the native presentation in these stressful areas.''}}</ref>\n\n== Reception ==\n=== Pre-release ===\nThe announcement trailer was met with a backlash from fans of the series who criticized the game for a lack of [[Historicity|historical accuracy]], authenticity and immersiveness. Complaints were given to the use of certain weapons, [[Prosthesis|prosthetics]], and body art as being very uncommon in that time period.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kain|first1=Erik|title=This 'Battlefield 5' Reveal Trailer Has Me More Confused Than Hyped|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/erikkain/2018/05/23/battlefield-5s-reveal-trailer-has-me-more-confused-than-hyped/#7cb0098156f9|website=Forbes|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180525205623/https://www.forbes.com/sites/erikkain/2018/05/23/battlefield-5s-reveal-trailer-has-me-more-confused-than-hyped |archive-date=May 25, 2018|access-date=May 25, 2018}}</ref> Some fans were also frustrated with the portrayal of women in the game, specifically with the British woman featured in the trailer as women never participated in [[Front line|frontline]] combat in the armed forces of Western Allies and were mostly relegated to supporting roles.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Groux|first1=Christopher|title='Battlefield V' Trailer Sparks Outrage, But Did Women Fight in World War II?|url=https://www.newsweek.com/battlefield-v-5-trailer-outrage-did-women-fight-world-war-2-943856|website=Newsweek|access-date=September 1, 2018}}</ref> Although acknowledging that women were rarely on the frontline, [[video game journalists]] have responded that there were some [[Women in World War II|female soldiers in World War II]], highlighting real-life examples from multiple countries, and that previous games in the ''Battlefield'' series are not seen as a completely realistic portrayal of war. Some also suggested that the backlash was partly due to [[misogyny]], rather than genuine worries over historical accuracy.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Plunkett|first1=Luke|title=Oh No, There Are Women In Battlefield V|url=https://kotaku.com/oh-no-there-are-women-in-battlefield-v-1826275455|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180530135530/https://kotaku.com/oh-no-there-are-women-in-battlefield-v-1826275455|archive-date=May 30, 2018|website=Kotaku|access-date=May 25, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Martin|first1=Matt|title=Battlefield 5 has women in it. If that bothers you, please, piss off|url=https://www.vg247.com/2018/05/24/battlefield-5-women-bothers-please-piss-off/|website=VG247|access-date=August 30, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Kim|first1=Matt|title=Battlefield 5 Doubles Down on the Representation of Women in World War II|url=https://www.usgamer.net/articles/battlefield-5-women-world-war-2|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180530135956/https://www.usgamer.net/articles/battlefield-5-women-world-war-2|archive-date=May 30, 2018|website=US Gamer|access-date=May 25, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Farokhmanesh|first1=Megan|title=Battlefield V fans who failed history are mad that the game has women in it|url=https://www.theverge.com/2018/5/24/17388414/battlefield-v-fans-game-women-world-war-2-history|archive-date=May 30, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180530140326/https://www.theverge.com/2018/5/24/17388414/battlefield-v-fans-game-women-world-war-2-history|website=The Verge|access-date=May 25, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn response to the outcry, the game's executive producer Aleksander Gr\u00f8ndal wrote on [[Twitter]] that the team would \"always put fun over authentic.\"<ref>{{cite web|first=Shabana|last=Arif|title=Battlefield V Producer Says DICE Will 'Always Put Fun Over Authentic'|url=http://uk.ign.com/articles/2018/05/24/battlefield-v-producer-says-dice-will-always-put-fun-over-authentic|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180530140512/http://www.ign.com/articles/2018/05/24/battlefield-v-producer-says-dice-will-always-put-fun-over-authentic|archive-date=May 30, 2018|website=IGN|date=May 24, 2018|access-date=May 25, 2018}}</ref> DICE's general manager Oskar Gabrielson also responded on Twitter, saying \"Player choice and female playable characters are here to stay ... Our commitment as a studio is to do everything we can to create games that are inclusive and diverse. We always set out to push boundaries and deliver unexpected experiences.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kane |first1=Alex |title=EA DICE Exec Fires Back About Women in \u2018Battlefield V' |url=https://variety.com/2018/gaming/news/battlefield-v-women-1202822531/ |website=Variety | date=May 25, 2018 | access-date=June 7, 2018 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180607153827/https://variety.com/2018/gaming/news/battlefield-v-women-1202822531/ | archive-date=June 7, 2018}}</ref> EA chief creative officer [[Patrick S\u00f6derlund]] said the developer was uninterested in taking flak for diversifying the gaming space. \"We stand up for the cause, because I think those people who don\u2019t understand it, well, you have two choices: either accept it or don\u2019t buy the game,\" he said. \"I\u2019m fine with either or.\" S\u00f6derlund went on to say that the development team itself pushed for women in ''Battlefield V''.<ref name=TV>{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2018/6/12/17453728/ea-women-in-battlefield-v-backlash-response|title=EA on the backlash against women in Battlefield V: \u2018Accept it or don\u2019t buy the game\u2019|last1=Farokhmanesh|first1=Megan|last2=Nicolett|first2=Megan|date=June 12, 2018}}</ref> In September, after the game was delayed by a month, DICE revealed they are planning on \"dialing back\" the character customization to attempt to \"give more authenticity to the game\", saying \"We want players to be excited about customizing their characters with authentic gear. We dialed it back a bit. It was pretty crazy, We wanted to offer some authenticity, and that\u2019s important to us, that\u2019s important to our players.\u201d<ref>{{cite web|title=DICE is \"dialling back\" Battlefield V\u2019s character customisation|url=https://www.pcgamesn.com/battlefield-v/battlefield-v-authentic-customisation|last=Jones|first=Ali|publisher=[[PCGamesN]]|date=September 13, 2018|access-date=September 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn August, the [[Cowen Group]], gaming industry analysts, reported that [[pre-order]] sales of ''Battlefield V'' were \"weak,\" being 85% behind those of ''[[Call of Duty: Black Ops 4]]''.<ref name=G>{{cite magazine|date=August 17, 2018|title=Former DICE CEO Patrick S\u00f6derlund Leaves Studio; Reveals Pre-Orders for Battlefield V are \u2018Weak\u2019|last=Hossam|first=Mostafa|magazine=[[Complex (magazine)|Gameranx]]|url=http://gameranx.com/updates/id/159331/article/former-dice-ceo-patrick-soderlund-leaves-studio-reveals-pre-orders-for-battlefield-v-are-weak/}}</ref><ref name=CNBC>{{cite web|date=August 20, 2018|title=Analyst predicts EA's 'Battlefield V' will be a 'serious disappointment,' says preorders lag 'Call of Duty' by more than 85%|last=Kim|first=Tae|publisher=[[CNBC]]|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/08/20/cowen-predicts-eas-battlefield-v-will-be-a-serious-disappointment-citing-weak-pre-orders.html}}</ref>\n\n=== Critical response ===\n{{Video game reviews\n| MC = (PC) 81/100<ref name=\"MCPC\">{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/pc/battlefield-v |title=Battlefield V for PC Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=November 17, 2018}}</ref><br />(PS4) 73/100<ref name=\"MCPS4\">{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/playstation-4/battlefield-v|title=Battlefield V for PlayStation 4 Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=November 17, 2018}}</ref><br />(XONE) 78/100<ref name=\"MCXONE\">{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/xbox-one/battlefield-v |title=Battlefield V for Xbox One Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=December 8, 2018}}</ref>\n| GI = 8/10<ref name=\"GI\">{{cite web |last1=Bertz |first1=Matt |title=Battlefield V Review \u2013 Hedge Warfare |url=https://www.gameinformer.com/review/battlefield-v/battlefield-v-review-hedge-warfare |website=[[Game Informer]]|accessdate=November 25, 2018}}</ref>\n| GRadar = {{Rating|3.5|5}}<ref name=\"GRadar\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gamesradar.com/battlefield-5-review/|title=Battlefield 5 review: \"Not as drastic a change up as its WW1 predecessor, nor as wild or wondrous\"|last=Avard|first=Alex|website=[[GamesRadar+]]|date=November 9, 2018|accessdate=November 25, 2018}}</ref>\n|IGN=7.5/10<ref>\n{{cite web \n|last = Duggan \n|first = James\n|date = November 29, 2018\n|url = https://www.ign.com/articles/2018/11/21/battlefield-v-review\n|title = Battlefield V Review\n|website = [[IGN]]\n|accessdate = August 30, 2019\n}}\n</ref>|PCGUK=79/100<ref>\n{{cite web \n|last = Kelly \n|first = Andy\n|date = November 13, 2018\n|url = https://www.pcgamer.com/uk/battlefield-5-review/\n|title = Battlefield V Review\n|website = [[PC Gamer]]\n|accessdate = August 30, 2019\n}}\n</ref>|GSpot=8/10<ref>\n{{cite web \n|last = Higham\n|first = Michael\n|date = November 20, 2018\n|url = https://www.gamespot.com/reviews/battlefield-5-review-breaking-through-the-front-li/1900-6417039/\n|title = Battlefield 5 Review - Breaking Through The Front Lines\n|website = [[GameSpot]]\n|accessdate = August 30, 2019\n}}\n</ref>|Destruct=8/10<ref>\n{{cite web \n|last = Devore\n|first = Jordan\n|date = November 11, 2018\n|url = https://www.destructoid.com/review-battlefield-v-530955.phtml\n|title = Review: Battlefield V\n|website = [[Destructoid]]\n|accessdate = August 30, 2019\n}}\n</ref>|GameRev={{Rating|2.5|5}}<ref>\n{{cite web \n|last = Russell \n|first = Bradley\n|date = November 26, 2018\n|url = https://www.gamerevolution.com/review/461663-battlefield-5-review-what-is-it-good-for\n|title = Battlefield 5 Review \u2013 What is it Good For?\n|website = [[Game Revolution]]\n|accessdate = August 30, 2019\n}}\n</ref>|PCGN=9/10<ref>\n{{cite web \n|last = McMahon \n|first = James\n|date = November 8, 2018\n|url = https://www.pcgamesn.com/battlefield-v-pc-review\n|title = Battlefield 5 PC review \u2013 the best the series has ever been\n|website = [[PCGamesN]]\n|accessdate = August 30, 2019\n}}\n</ref>|rev1=''[[PC World]]''|rev1Score={{Rating|4.5|5}}<ref>\n{{cite web \n|last = Dingman \n|first = Hayden\n|date = November 20, 2018\n|url = https://www.pcworld.com/article/3322617/battlefield-v-review.html\n|title = Battlefield V review: World War II never changes\n|website = [[PC World]]\n|accessdate = August 30, 2019\n}}\n</ref>|rev2=''[[Digital Trends]]''|rev2Score={{Rating|3|5}}<ref>\n{{cite web \n|last = Gurwin \n|first = Gabe\n|date = November 12, 2018\n|url = https://www.digitaltrends.com/game-reviews/battlefield-v-review/\n|title = Battlefield V review\n|website = [[Digital Trends]]\n|accessdate = August 30, 2019\n}}\n</ref>}}\n\nAccording to review aggregator [[Metacritic]], ''Battlefield V'' received \"generally favorable\" reviews for the PC and Xbox One versions and \"mixed or average\" reviews for the PlayStation 4 version.<ref name=\"MCPC\"/><ref name=\"MCPS4\"/><ref name=\"MCXONE\"/>\n\nIn ''[[Game Informer]]''{{'}}s 8/10 review, they wrote, \"Ultimately, ''Battlefield V'' will be defined by the success or failure of the pending Combined Arms cooperative mode, Firestorm battle royale mode, and whether or not DICE can continually provide new and engaging content.\"<ref name= GI/> ''[[GamesRadar+]]'' gave the game 3.5/5 stars, praising the gameplay but criticizing the online multiplayer, writing: \"Not as drastic a change up as its WW1 predecessor, nor as wild or wondrous, ''Battlefield 5''{{'}}s deliberative design sidelines its strengths as a simulative sandbox.\"<ref name=GRadar/>\n\n=== Sales ===\n\nIn November, it was reported that ''Battlefield V'' sold fewer than half the physical copies that ''Battlefield 1'' did upon its launch during the same period of time.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2018-11-26-battlefield-5-physical-sales-down-more-than-half-on-battlefield-1|title=Battlefield 5 physical sales down more than half on Battlefield 1|last=Phillips|first=Tom|website=[[Eurogamer]]|date=November 26, 2018|accessdate=November 28, 2018}}</ref> The game sold 7.3 million copies by the end of 2018. On February 5, 2019, EA's CEO Andrew Wilson announced that the game ultimately failed to meet sales expectations, blaming the game's marketing as well as their focus on developing a single-player campaign instead of a [[Battle royale game|battle royale]] mode, a genre which had gained recent widespread popularity. Wilson also highlighted ''Battlefield V''{{'}}s long development cycle, and release in a month of strong competition. EA's stock prices also faced its worst drop in more than a decade during its third quarter of the fiscal year, declining by around 18 percent, which EA attributed in part to the poor sales of the game.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Makuch |first1=Eddie |title=Battlefield 5 Fails To Meet Sales Targets, And EA Explains Why |url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/battlefield-5-fails-to-meet-sales-targets-and-ea-e/1100-6464832/ |website=GameSpot |accessdate=February 7, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Brown |first1=Fraser |title=Battlefield 5 did not meet EA's sales expectations |url=https://www.pcgamer.com/battlefield-5-did-not-meet-eas-sales-expectations/ |website=PC Gamer |accessdate=February 7, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Nunneley |first1=Stephany |title=Battlefield 5 sales didn\u2019t meet expectations during Q3, says EA |url=https://www.vg247.com/2019/02/05/battlefield-5-sales-didnt-meet-expectations/ |website=VG247 |accessdate=February 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn Japan, the PlayStation 4 version of ''Battlefield V'' sold 110,653 during its first week of release, placing it at number four on the all format sales chart.<ref>{{cite web |last=Romano |first=Sal |date=November 28, 2018 |url=https://gematsu.com/2018/11/media-create-sales-11-19-18-11-25-18 |title=Media Create Sales: 11/19/18 \u2013 11/25/18 |publisher=Gematsu |accessdate=May 18, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Awards ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Award !! Category !! Result !! Ref\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"7\" | 2018\n| rowspan=\"3\" | [[Game Critics Awards]]\n| Best PC Game\n| {{Nom}}\n| rowspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/resident-evil-2-wins-top-honor-in-e3-game-critics-/1100-6460135/|title=Resident Evil 2 Wins Top Honor In E3 Game Critics Awards|last=Watts|first=Steve|website=[[GameSpot]]|date=July 5, 2018|accessdate=January 11, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| Best Action Game\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| Best Online Multiplayer\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| [[2018 Golden Joystick Awards]]\n| Most Wanted Game\n| {{Nom}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>