{"title_page": "Thokoza", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement\n| name                    = Thokoza\n| other_name              = Menoldin\n| image_skyline           = CPT-JNB 18.08.2009 07-44-00.jpg\n| image_caption           = Aerial view of Thokoza\n| pushpin_map             = South Africa Gauteng#South Africa\n| coordinates             = {{coord|26|20|12|S|28|08|48|E|region:ZA|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type        = Country\n| subdivision_name        = [[South Africa]]\n| subdivision_type1       = Province\n| subdivision_name1       = [[Gauteng]]\n| subdivision_type2       = District\n| subdivision_type3       = Municipality\n| subdivision_name3       = [[Ekurhuleni Metropolitan Municipality|Ekurhuleni]]\n| subdivision_type4       = Main Place\n| established_title       = Established\n| leader_title            = Councillor\n| area_footnotes          = <ref name=\"census2011\">{{cite web |url=http://census2011.adrianfrith.com/place/797030 |title = Main Place Thokoza |work=Census 2011}} </ref>\n| area_total_km2          = 9.43\n| population_footnotes    = <ref name=\"census2011\" />\n| population_total        = 105827\n| population_as_of        = 2011\n| population_density_km2  = auto\n<!-- demographics (section 1) -->\n| demographics_type1      = Racial makeup (2011)\n| demographics1_footnotes = <ref name=\"census2011\" />\n| demographics1_title1    = [[Bantu peoples of South Africa|African]]\n| demographics1_info1     = 99.1%\n| demographics1_title2    = [[Coloureds|Coloured]]\n| demographics1_info2     = 0.4%\n| demographics1_title3    = [[Indian South African|Indian]]/[[Asian South African|Asian]]\n| demographics1_info3     = 0.1%\n| demographics1_title4    = [[White South African|Caucasian]]\n| demographics1_info4     = 0.1%\n| demographics1_title5    = Other\n| demographics1_info5     = 0.2%\n<!-- demographics (section 2) -->\n| demographics_type2      = [[First language]]s (2011)\n| demographics2_footnotes = <ref name=\"census2011\" />\n| demographics2_title1    = [[Zulu language|Zulu]]\n| demographics2_info1     = 40.2%\n| demographics2_title2    = [[Sotho language|Sotho]]\n| demographics2_info2     = 21.5%\n| demographics2_title3    = [[Xhosa language|Xhosa]]\n| demographics2_info3     = 18.4%\n| demographics2_title4    = [[Northern Sotho language|Northern Sotho]]\n| demographics2_info4     = 5.4%\n| demographics2_title5    = Other\n| demographics2_info5     = 14.5%\n<!-- blank fields (section 2) -->\n<!-- Other information -->\n| timezone1               = [[South African Standard Time|SAST]]\n| utc_offset1             = +2\n| postal_code_type        = [[List of postal codes in South Africa|Postal code]] (street)\n| postal_code             = 1426\n| postal2_code_type       = [[Post-office box|PO box]]\n| postal2_code            = 1421\n| area_code_type          = [[Telephone numbers in South Africa|Area code]]\n}}\n'''Thokoza''' is a [[Township (South Africa)|township]] in [[City of Ekurhuleni Metropolitan Municipality|Ekurhuleni]], Gauteng.  Thokoza is at the location of the now defunct [[Palmietfontein Airport]]. It is situated south east of [[Alberton, Gauteng|Alberton]], adjacent to [[Katlehong]]. Thokoza was the first black township which was established in the East Rand. During the early 1990s Thokoza was the middle of unrest between the supporters of the [[Inkatha Freedom Party]] (IFP), rival party of the [[African National Congress]] (ANC).<ref>http://www.sowetanlive.co.za/news/2011/06/28/thokoza-looks-back-at-its-bang-bang-days</ref>\n\n==History==\nIn 1955, the [[Germiston]] and Alberton municipalities swapped land and the latter received part of the land that made up the Natalspruit area, which was needed to form a new black township.<ref name=\"Marx\">{{cite web | url=http://www.urbanlandmark.org.za/downloads/Land_Biographies_Full_Report_LowRes.pdf | title=\u2018Divisible Spaces\u2019: Land Biographies in Diepkloof, Thokoza and Doornfontein, Gauteng | work=Urban LandMark | date=May 2008 | accessdate=24 December 2015 | author1=Marx, Colin | author2=Rubin, Margot | pages=136}}</ref>{{rp|54}} From 1958-59, the Alberton municipality begun to develop a new township on the [[Palmietfontein Airport|Palmietfontein]] section.<ref name=Marx/>{{rp|54}} Each plot was to be serviced with a basic water and sewerage infrastructure, with the building of a one bedroom shack and later one, two or three bedroom houses.<ref name=Marx/>{{rp|54}}  The new township would be called ''Thokoza'' (place of peace).<ref name=Marx/>{{rp|54}}  By 1961 all black residents of locations within the Alberton municipality had been moved to the new township after a registration process and the issuing of plot locations.<ref name=Marx/>{{rp|54\u20135}}\n\nAll this was in aid of carrying out the introduction of the Apartheid governments ''[[Native (Urban Areas) Consolidation Act]]'', which controlled the movement of the black population in the country to certain areas of work and residence. Financially, municipalities were aided in this process by the enactment of two new laws in the 1950s. ''[[Native Building Workers Act, 1951|Bantu Building Workers' Act (1950)]]'' which allowed black workers, on low wages, to build the houses and infrastructure and the ''Bantu Services Levy Act (1952)'' which paid for the new building work by levying the wages of black employees in the country.<ref name=Marx/>{{rp|54}}\n\nFrom 1961 until 1981, three hostels, ''Madala'', ''Buyafuthi'' and ''Umshayzafe'' were constructed for migrant labour and situated along Khumalo Road, the main road in the city which stretches for over seven kilometers.<ref name=Marx/>{{rp|55}} Khumalo Street would be named after Jacon Khumalo, a migrant worker from Vryheid, KwaZulu-Natal and who was a community leader in 1960s and whose house is still found along the road.<ref name=\"SABC01\">{{cite web | url=http://www.sabc.co.za/news/a/67ffae8043c14432a90afb239b19c088/Khumalo-street-in-East-Rand--is-remembered--20140424 | title=Khumalo street in East Rand is remembered | publisher=South African Broadcasting Commission | date=24 April 2014 | accessdate=24 December 2015 | author=ka'Nkosi, Sechaba}}</ref> The hostels were created for 2500 men but by the 1980s the popolutation residing in them had risen to as high as 13,000 split along ethnic, social and language groups.<ref name=Marx/>{{rp|55}} This tended to isolated the hostel dwellers from the township dwellers and led to tension in later years.<ref name=Marx/>{{rp|55}} By the late 1960s, crime levels grew in the region as social conditions deteriorated and employment dropped.<ref name=Marx/>{{rp|58}}\n\nIn 1972, [[Piet Koornhof]], then Minister of Bantu Administration, established the [[East Rand Administration Board]] (ERAB) and with that removed 4058ha of Thokoza from the Alberton municipality with the management of the land now under control of the new board and more directly the South African governments apartheid land policies.<ref name=Marx/>{{rp|58}} After 1982, the township would gain municipality status from the East Rand Administration Board.<ref name=\"Townships\">{{cite web | url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=PezSAAAAMAAJ&q=Thokoza&dq=Thokoza&hl=en&sa=X&redir_esc=y | title=Townships of the PWV | publisher=South African Institute of Race Relations | date=1988 | accessdate=24 December 2015 | author=Mashabela, Harry | pages=184 | ISBN=9780869823439}}</ref> The board would fail to alleviate the shortages of land and housing for the black population region, with most of financial resources provided used to manage the board itself.<ref name=Marx/>{{rp|58}} The population increased from between 27,000 and 48,000 between 1970 and 1975, despite no further land or house being issued.<ref name=Marx/>{{rp|59}} The main reason for the increase in population during this period was development of the Alrode industrial area adjacent to Thokoza that resulted in further employment opportunities.<ref name=Marx/>{{rp|59}} Despite the requests of the ERAB for further funding for development, the South African government failed to provide it.<ref name=Marx/>{{rp|59\u201360}}\n\nOn 17 June 1976, Thokoza residents joined in the protests what became known as the [[Soweto uprising]] that had started in the township of [[Soweto]] the day before, brought about by the introduction of [[Afrikaans]] as the medium of instruction in local schools, and resulted in a week of violent protests.<ref name=Marx/>{{rp|58}}\n\nThe 1980s saw the rise of the backyard shack dwellers and informal settlements on open land, with two shacks for every formal house in Thokoza and by 1992, the shacks ratio had doubled.<ref name=Marx/>{{rp|60}} Forced removals would be the option used by local government to try to maintain control of the city, after the introduction of monthly levies to be paid by shack dwellers failed to move them on.<ref name=Marx/>{{rp|60}}\n\nBy the mid 1980s, rent boycotts and the failure to pay for utility services started, mostly as a protest against the black local government.<ref name=Marx/>{{rp|61}} Soon law and order fell apart, and students, trade unionists, street committees, hostel-dwellers and gangsters filled the vacuum brought about by the lack of political expression by the occupants of Thokoza.<ref name=Marx/>{{rp|61\u20132}}\n\nIn 1990, the population had reached 228,000 and the initial infrastructure provided by the Alberton municipality in the 1960s had begun to fail with the lack of water and the failure of sewage systems being the most serious issues.<ref name=Marx/>{{rp|61}}\n\nIn the early 1990s, prior to the [[South African general election, 1994|1994 elections]], political tensions developed between the township dwellers and the hostel residents, split by political affiliations, the [[African National Congress]] (ANC) or the [[Inkatha Freedom Party]] (IFP).<ref name=SABC01/> In October 1999, the leaders of both the ANC and IFP met in Thokoza's Khumalo Road, to commemorate at a community-memorial, the 688 people who died during the violence in the early 1990s, and to symbolize a spirit of healing and reconciliation in the community.<ref name=\"Struggle\">{{cite web | url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=Yf3GGmLNwdkC&pg=PT61&dq=Thokoza&hl=en&sa=X&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=Thokoza&f=false | title=Struggle: Volume 6 of South Africa's top sites | publisher=New Africa Books | date=2004 | accessdate=25 December 2015 | author=Harrison, Philip | pages=104}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{City of Ekurhuleni Metropolitan Municipality}}\n\n[[Category:Townships in Gauteng]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1973]]\n[[Category:Populated places in Ekurhuleni]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n| name                    = Thokoza\n| other_name              = Menoldin\n| image_skyline           = CPT-JNB 18.08.2009 07-44-00.jpg\n| image_caption           = Aerial view of Thokoza\n| pushpin_map             = South Africa Gauteng#South Africa\n| coordinates             = {{coord|26|20|12|S|28|08|48|E|region:ZA|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type        = Country\n| subdivision_name        = [[South Africa]]\n| subdivision_type1       = Province\n| subdivision_name1       = [[Gauteng]]\n| subdivision_type2       = District\n| subdivision_type3       = Municipality\n| subdivision_name3       = [[Ekurhuleni Metropolitan Municipality|Ekurhuleni]]\n| subdivision_type4       = Main Place\n| established_title       = Established\n| leader_title            = Councillor\n| area_footnotes          = <ref name=\"census2011\">{{cite web |url=http://census2011.adrianfrith.com/place/797030 |title = Main Place Thokoza |work=Census 2011}} </ref>\n| area_total_km2          = 9.43\n| population_footnotes    = <ref name=\"census2011\" />\n| population_total        = 105827\n| population_as_of        = 2011\n| population_density_km2  = auto\n<!-- demographics (section 1) -->\n| demographics_type1      = Racial makeup (2011)\n| demographics1_footnotes = <ref name=\"census2011\" />\n| demographics1_title1    = [[Bantu peoples of South Africa|Black African]]\n| demographics1_info1     = 99.1%\n| demographics1_title2    = [[Coloureds|Coloured]]\n| demographics1_info2     = 0.4%\n| demographics1_title3    = [[Indian South African|Indian]]/[[Asian South African|Asian]]\n| demographics1_info3     = 0.1%\n| demographics1_title4    = [[White South African|White]]\n| demographics1_info4     = 0.1%\n| demographics1_title5    = Other\n| demographics1_info5     = 0.2%\n<!-- demographics (section 2) -->\n| demographics_type2      = [[First language]]s (2011)\n| demographics2_footnotes = <ref name=\"census2011\" />\n| demographics2_title1    = [[Zulu language|Zulu]]\n| demographics2_info1     = 40.2%\n| demographics2_title2    = [[Sotho language|Sotho]]\n| demographics2_info2     = 21.5%\n| demographics2_title3    = [[Xhosa language|Xhosa]]\n| demographics2_info3     = 18.4%\n| demographics2_title4    = [[Northern Sotho language|Northern Sotho]]\n| demographics2_info4     = 5.4%\n| demographics2_title5    = Other\n| demographics2_info5     = 14.5%\n<!-- blank fields (section 2) -->\n<!-- Other information -->\n| timezone1               = [[South African Standard Time|SAST]]\n| utc_offset1             = +2\n| postal_code_type        = [[List of postal codes in South Africa|Postal code]] (street)\n| postal_code             = 1426\n| postal2_code_type       = [[Post-office box|PO box]]\n| postal2_code            = 1421\n| area_code_type          = [[Telephone numbers in South Africa|Area code]]\n}}\n'''Thokoza''' is a [[Township (South Africa)|township]] in [[City of Ekurhuleni Metropolitan Municipality|Ekurhuleni]], Gauteng.  Thokoza is at the location of the now defunct [[Palmietfontein Airport]]. It is situated south east of [[Alberton, Gauteng|Alberton]], adjacent to [[Katlehong]]. Thokoza was the first black township which was established in the East Rand. During the early 1990s Thokoza was the middle of unrest between the supporters of the [[Inkatha Freedom Party]] (IFP), rival party of the [[African National Congress]] (ANC).<ref>http://www.sowetanlive.co.za/news/2011/06/28/thokoza-looks-back-at-its-bang-bang-days</ref>\n\n==History==\nIn 1955, the [[Germiston]] and Alberton municipalities swapped land and the latter received part of the land that made up the Natalspruit area, which was needed to form a new black township.<ref name=\"Marx\">{{cite web | url=http://www.urbanlandmark.org.za/downloads/Land_Biographies_Full_Report_LowRes.pdf | title=\u2018Divisible Spaces\u2019: Land Biographies in Diepkloof, Thokoza and Doornfontein, Gauteng | work=Urban LandMark | date=May 2008 | accessdate=24 December 2015 | author1=Marx, Colin | author2=Rubin, Margot | pages=136}}</ref>{{rp|54}} From 1958-59, the Alberton municipality begun to develop a new township on the [[Palmietfontein Airport|Palmietfontein]] section.<ref name=Marx/>{{rp|54}} Each plot was to be serviced with a basic water and sewerage infrastructure, with the building of a one bedroom shack and later one, two or three bedroom houses.<ref name=Marx/>{{rp|54}}  The new township would be called ''Thokoza'' (place of peace).<ref name=Marx/>{{rp|54}}  By 1961 all black residents of locations within the Alberton municipality had been moved to the new township after a registration process and the issuing of plot locations.<ref name=Marx/>{{rp|54\u20135}}\n\nAll this was in aid of carrying out the introduction of the Apartheid governments ''[[Native (Urban Areas) Consolidation Act]]'', which controlled the movement of the black population in the country to certain areas of work and residence. Financially, municipalities were aided in this process by the enactment of two new laws in the 1950s. ''[[Native Building Workers Act, 1951|Bantu Building Workers' Act (1950)]]'' which allowed black workers, on low wages, to build the houses and infrastructure and the ''Bantu Services Levy Act (1952)'' which paid for the new building work by levying the wages of black employees in the country.<ref name=Marx/>{{rp|54}}\n\nFrom 1961 until 1981, three hostels, ''Madala'', ''Buyafuthi'' and ''Umshayzafe'' were constructed for migrant labour and situated along Khumalo Road, the main road in the city which stretches for over seven kilometers.<ref name=Marx/>{{rp|55}} Khumalo Street would be named after Jacon Khumalo, a migrant worker from Vryheid, KwaZulu-Natal and who was a community leader in 1960s and whose house is still found along the road.<ref name=\"SABC01\">{{cite web | url=http://www.sabc.co.za/news/a/67ffae8043c14432a90afb239b19c088/Khumalo-street-in-East-Rand--is-remembered--20140424 | title=Khumalo street in East Rand is remembered | publisher=South African Broadcasting Commission | date=24 April 2014 | accessdate=24 December 2015 | author=ka'Nkosi, Sechaba}}</ref> The hostels were created for 2500 men but by the 1980s the popolutation residing in them had risen to as high as 13,000 split along ethnic, social and language groups.<ref name=Marx/>{{rp|55}} This tended to isolated the hostel dwellers from the township dwellers and led to tension in later years.<ref name=Marx/>{{rp|55}} By the late 1960s, crime levels grew in the region as social conditions deteriorated and employment dropped.<ref name=Marx/>{{rp|58}}\n\nIn 1972, [[Piet Koornhof]], then Minister of Bantu Administration, established the [[East Rand Administration Board]] (ERAB) and with that removed 4058ha of Thokoza from the Alberton municipality with the management of the land now under control of the new board and more directly the South African governments apartheid land policies.<ref name=Marx/>{{rp|58}} After 1982, the township would gain municipality status from the East Rand Administration Board.<ref name=\"Townships\">{{cite web | url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=PezSAAAAMAAJ&q=Thokoza&dq=Thokoza&hl=en&sa=X&redir_esc=y | title=Townships of the PWV | publisher=South African Institute of Race Relations | date=1988 | accessdate=24 December 2015 | author=Mashabela, Harry | pages=184 | ISBN=9780869823439}}</ref> The board would fail to alleviate the shortages of land and housing for the black population region, with most of financial resources provided used to manage the board itself.<ref name=Marx/>{{rp|58}} The population increased from between 27,000 and 48,000 between 1970 and 1975, despite no further land or house being issued.<ref name=Marx/>{{rp|59}} The main reason for the increase in population during this period was development of the Alrode industrial area adjacent to Thokoza that resulted in further employment opportunities.<ref name=Marx/>{{rp|59}} Despite the requests of the ERAB for further funding for development, the South African government failed to provide it.<ref name=Marx/>{{rp|59\u201360}}\n\nOn 17 June 1976, Thokoza residents joined in the protests what became known as the [[Soweto uprising]] that had started in the township of [[Soweto]] the day before, brought about by the introduction of [[Afrikaans]] as the medium of instruction in local schools, and resulted in a week of violent protests.<ref name=Marx/>{{rp|58}}\n\nThe 1980s saw the rise of the backyard shack dwellers and informal settlements on open land, with two shacks for every formal house in Thokoza and by 1992, the shacks ratio had doubled.<ref name=Marx/>{{rp|60}} Forced removals would be the option used by local government to try to maintain control of the city, after the introduction of monthly levies to be paid by shack dwellers failed to move them on.<ref name=Marx/>{{rp|60}}\n\nBy the mid 1980s, rent boycotts and the failure to pay for utility services started, mostly as a protest against the black local government.<ref name=Marx/>{{rp|61}} Soon law and order fell apart, and students, trade unionists, street committees, hostel-dwellers and gangsters filled the vacuum brought about by the lack of political expression by the occupants of Thokoza.<ref name=Marx/>{{rp|61\u20132}}\n\nIn 1990, the population had reached 228,000 and the initial infrastructure provided by the Alberton municipality in the 1960s had begun to fail with the lack of water and the failure of sewage systems being the most serious issues.<ref name=Marx/>{{rp|61}}\n\nIn the early 1990s, prior to the [[South African general election, 1994|1994 elections]], political tensions developed between the township dwellers and the hostel residents, split by political affiliations, the [[African National Congress]] (ANC) or the [[Inkatha Freedom Party]] (IFP).<ref name=SABC01/> In October 1999, the leaders of both the ANC and IFP met in Thokoza's Khumalo Road, to commemorate at a community-memorial, the 688 people who died during the violence in the early 1990s, and to symbolize a spirit of healing and reconciliation in the community.<ref name=\"Struggle\">{{cite web | url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=Yf3GGmLNwdkC&pg=PT61&dq=Thokoza&hl=en&sa=X&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=Thokoza&f=false | title=Struggle: Volume 6 of South Africa's top sites | publisher=New Africa Books | date=2004 | accessdate=25 December 2015 | author=Harrison, Philip | pages=104}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{City of Ekurhuleni Metropolitan Municipality}}\n\n[[Category:Townships in Gauteng]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1973]]\n[[Category:Populated places in Ekurhuleni]]\n", "name_user": "196.21.159.6", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thokoza"}
